title: For Sale:  Sig Sauer P228 9mm MINT CONDITION
postcontent:
This is truly what they call a mint condition handgun, and is probably the best example of what my for sale ads mean when they refer to a lot of my guns and accessories as being "time-capsuled." This gun is almost 20 years old (19 to be exact), and yet looks like it just came from the manufacturer and landed on a Dealers' shelf. It's in pristine condition, with only a very, very,very slight 1/4 inch straight scratch along the exact edge of the slide where it sat in my computer desk, and another tiny pinprick dot (1/16 of an inch) also on the slide edge where it must've contacted the surface of the desk drawer. The gun was shot exactly twice in 19 years, probably the first weekend I bought it, and has sat in my computer desk ever since 1994... This is old school, vintage Sig Sauer P228 where it all began about 20 years ago, with its then adoption by the FBI as a primary duty weapon. It's interesting to see that the design of this gun has been so successful that it has barely been modified in nearly 20 years. Interesting too is the fact I did notice a few years ago they did try once to tinker with a re-design of the P228, but are now back again re-issuing this classic design calling it their M11 variant, but it is essentially this same gun, just with night sights. This gun is to Sigs, what the original 80's era Gen 1 Glocks are to Glocks...Comes with original box and original manual, 2 original 13 round mags.  

 That said, though the condition on this is truly mint and it's barely been touched in 19 years, I could see how someone might hesitate spending this amount of money on what is still technically a "used gun" (although probably vintage by now), and so I do have a BRAND NEW HK P2000 SK 9mm with night sights still available, just check my other ad links, it should be there.

title: For Sale:  LWRC REPR Black 308 16" Spiral Fluted REPRR7BF16
postcontent: This rifle features a 16" barrel with LWRC's signature spiral fluting, which reduces weight and improves heat dissipation, while relieving the longitudinal stresses experienced by conventionally linearly fluted barrels. LWRC rifles and carbines utilize cold hammer forged barrels made out of 41V45 steel alloy and treated with NiCorr surface conversion technology. Cold hammer forging takes an oversized barrel blank, and using high pressure rotary hammers, compacts the barrel blank over a mandrel. This forms perfect rifling devoid of tool marks. It also compacts the molecular structure of the metal making it denser and stronger. These barrels can take a lot more use and abuse than a standard barrel before any degradation in accuracy or loss of velocity. NiCorr surface conversion has proved more lubricious, harder wearing, more heat and corrosion resistant than the hard chrome normally used in the bore. LWRC claims their barrels can handle 20,000 rounds before replacement, as compared to 6,000-10,000 rounds on a standard M4.

title: For Sale:  LWRC REPR Black 308 16" Spiral Fluted REPRR7BF16
location: New Mexico, New Mexico, United States
postcontent: This rifle features a 16" barrel with LWRC's signature spiral fluting, which reduces weight and improves heat dissipation, while relieving the longitudinal stresses experienced by conventionally linearly fluted barrels. LWRC rifles and carbines utilize cold hammer forged barrels made out of 41V45 steel alloy and treated with NiCorr surface conversion technology. Cold hammer forging takes an oversized barrel blank, and using high pressure rotary hammers, compacts the barrel blank over a mandrel. This forms perfect rifling devoid of tool marks. It also compacts the molecular structure of the metal making it denser and stronger. These barrels can take a lot more use and abuse than a standard barrel before any degradation in accuracy or loss of velocity. NiCorr surface conversion has proved more lubricious, harder wearing, more heat and corrosion resistant than the hard chrome normally used in the bore. LWRC claims their barrels can handle 20,000 rounds before replacement, as compared to 6,000-10,000 rounds on a standard M4.
